<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1436,1120,2027]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,1120,1146]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carico. A" authorityYear="1981" box="[336,566,1121,1146]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capricorna">
<emphasis box="[336,566,1121,1146]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Architis capricorna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the largest species in the genus, and shares several characters of male and female genitalia with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carico. A" authorityYear="1981" box="[457,578,1161,1186]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robusta">
<emphasis box="[457,578,1161,1186]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A. robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos" authorityYear="2007" baseAuthorityName="Mello-Leitao" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[636,804,1161,1186]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[636,804,1161,1186]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A. brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[812,946,1160,1186]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[812,946,1160,1186]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(see 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carico. A" authorityYear="1981" box="[1009,1130,1161,1186]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robusta">
<emphasis box="[1009,1130,1161,1186]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A. robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
diagnosis). These species can be differentiated by the prolaterally notched VTA and the shape of vRTA and dRTA which have a common base and a peculiar spermduct in the anterior margin of the DTP which is shaped like a string of beads in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carico. A" authorityYear="1981" box="[151,314,1281,1306]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capricorna">
<emphasis box="[151,314,1281,1306]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A. capricorna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[329,477,1281,1307]" captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="35.[151,269,1530,1554]" captionTargetBox="[304,1286,196,1486]" captionTargetId="figure-202@35.[252,1335,124,1506]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 19A–E. Architis capricorna Carico. A, male pedipalpus, ventral view; B, male pedipalpus, lateral view; C, female tarsus IV, apex, prolatero-ventral view; D, female epigynum, ventral view; E, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. The arrow points to the retrolateral projection of the VTA. The embolus can be seen arising close to conductor and through the transparent DTP. Scale bars: A–B, 0.2 mm; C–E, 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097233/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Figs 19A, B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[489,543,1281,1307]" captionStart="FIGURES 20" captionStartId="36.[151,269,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[193,1394,194,1807]" captionTargetId="figure-79@36.[193,1394,194,1807]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 20A–C. Architis spp. (SEM). A–B, A. brasiliensis (Mello-Leitão): A, male pedipalpus, ventral view; B, female internal genitalia, detail of left copulatory duct and spermatheca, dorsal view. C–D: A. capricorna Carico; C, male pedipalpus, ventral view; D, male pedipalpus, conductor, ventral view. * indicates prolateral lobe of conductor. Scale bars: A, C–D, 100 µm; B, 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097243" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097243/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">20C</figureCitation>
). Females can be recognised by the specially elongated spiral of the copulatory ducts and the spherical spermathecae (
<figureCitation box="[655,762,1321,1347]" captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="35.[151,269,1530,1554]" captionTargetBox="[304,1286,196,1486]" captionTargetId="figure-202@35.[252,1335,124,1506]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 19A–E. Architis capricorna Carico. A, male pedipalpus, ventral view; B, male pedipalpus, lateral view; C, female tarsus IV, apex, prolatero-ventral view; D, female epigynum, ventral view; E, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. The arrow points to the retrolateral projection of the VTA. The embolus can be seen arising close to conductor and through the transparent DTP. Scale bars: A–B, 0.2 mm; C–E, 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097233/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 19E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
